cells","Exclusively promote resolution of inflammation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContribute to both tissue destruction and repair processes\u003C/strong\u003E accurately describes the dual role of macrophages in chronic inflammation. Macrophages secrete mediators that can damage tissues (such as reactive oxygen species, nitric oxide, and proteolytic enzymes) while also producing growth factors and cytokines that initiate tissue repair and fibrosis. This balance between destructive and reparative functions is central to their role in chronic inflammatory responses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimarily function to present antigens to B lymphocytes\u003C/strong\u003E - Although macrophages can present antigens, they primarily present to T lymphocytes rather than B lymphocytes. Additionally, antigen presentation is just one of many important functions of macrophages in chronic inflammation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EServe as the main source of immunoglobulin production\u003C/strong\u003E - Immunoglobulins are produced by plasma cells derived from B lymphocytes, not by macrophages.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimarily function to induce apoptosis of damaged cells\u003C/strong\u003E - While macrophages can clear apoptotic cells, this is not their primary function in chronic inflammation. Their roles in secreting inflammatory mediators, phagocytosis, and tissue repair are more significant.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExclusively promote resolution of inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect because macrophages have dual functions. While alternatively activated (M2) macrophages promote resolution and repair, classically activated (M1) macrophages promote inflammation and tissue damage.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMacrophages can be activated through classical (M1) or alternative (M2) pathways. M1 macrophages are induced by microbial products and interferon-gamma, and they promote inflammation through production of nitric oxide and pro-inflammatory cytokines. M2 macrophages are induced by IL-4 and IL-13, and they promote tissue repair and resolution of inflammation. The balance between these activation states influences the progression and outcome of chronic inflammatory responses.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Macrophages are the dominant cells in chronic inflammation and contribute by secreting cytokines, destroying foreign invaders, and activating other cells.","Macrophages can be activated via classical (M1) or alternative (M2) pathways, with M1 promoting inflammation and M2 promoting tissue repair.","Macrophages have dual roles in chronic inflammation, contributing to both tissue destruction through inflammatory mediators and tissue repair through growth factors."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 3, Inflammation and Repair; p. 97-100"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79529"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20722"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79529"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-03T13:35:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T13:38:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13598"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96914"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"d